webpackJsonp([0xc3fb1536e8dc5800],{"./node_modules/json-loader/index.js!./.cache/json/ruby-ruby-hashes.json":function(a,s){a.exports={data:{markdownRemark:{html:'<h2>Ruby Hashes</h2>\n<p>A hash is a collection of keys and values. It is similar to what is commonly called a dictionary in other languages. In Ruby, a hash is similar to an <a href=\'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/freeCodeCamp/guides/master/src/pages/ruby/ruby-arrays/index.md\' target=\'_blank\' rel=\'nofollow\'>array</a>, but rather than simply storing a value it stores a key, value pair.</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-ruby"><code>array <span class="token operator">=</span> <span class="token punctuation">[</span><span class="token string">"value"</span><span class="token punctuation">]</span>\nhash <span class="token operator">=</span> <span class="token punctuation">{</span> <span class="token string">"key"</span> <span class="token operator">=</span><span class="token operator">></span> <span class="token string">"value"</span> <span class="token punctuation">}</span>\n</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>There are a couple of different ways to create a new hash:</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-ruby"><code>hash1 <span class="token operator">=</span> <span class="token punctuation">{</span>a<span class="token punctuation">:</span> <span class="token number">100</span><span class="token punctuation">,</span> b<span class="token punctuation">:</span> <span class="token string">"200"</span><span class="token punctuation">}</span>\nhash2 <span class="token operator">=</span> <span class="token builtin">Hash</span><span class="token punctuation">.</span><span class="token keyword">new</span>\n</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>A programmer can then access a hash value using its key, rather than the index.</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-ruby"><code>array<span class="token punctuation">[</span><span class="token number">0</span><span class="token punctuation">]</span> <span class="token comment" spellcheck="true"># => "value"</span>\nhash<span class="token punctuation">[</span><span class="token string">"key"</span><span class="token punctuation">]</span> <span class="token comment" spellcheck="true"># => "value" </span>\n</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>In this way, a hash acts more like a dictionary where you can look up a value by its key.</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-ruby"><code>dictionary <span class="token operator">=</span> <span class="token punctuation">{</span> <span class="token string">"Aardvark"</span> <span class="token operator">=</span><span class="token operator">></span> <span class="token string">"a large, nocturnal, burrowing mammal"</span><span class="token punctuation">,</span> \n               <span class="token string">"Zyzzyva"</span> <span class="token operator">=</span><span class="token operator">></span> <span class="token string">"a genus of tropical weevils"</span> <span class="token punctuation">}</span>\ndictionary<span class="token punctuation">[</span><span class="token string">"Aardvark"</span><span class="token punctuation">]</span> <span class="token comment" spellcheck="true"># => "a large, nocturnal, burrowing mammal"</span>\ndictionary<span class="token punctuation">[</span><span class="token string">"Zyzzyva"</span><span class="token punctuation">]</span> <span class="token comment" spellcheck="true"># => "a genus of tropical weevils"</span>\n</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>You can also create a hash using <a href="#">symbols</a> as keys.</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-ruby"><code>hash <span class="token operator">=</span> <span class="token punctuation">{</span> <span class="token symbol">:symbol</span> <span class="token operator">=</span><span class="token operator">></span> <span class="token string">"value"</span> <span class="token punctuation">}</span>\nhash<span class="token punctuation">[</span><span class="token symbol">:symbol</span><span class="token punctuation">]</span> <span class="token comment" spellcheck="true"># => "value"</span>\n</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>In addition, if all of your keys are <a href="#">symbols</a>, you can write your hash in this alternate format, but you would access it in the same manner:</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-ruby"><code>hash <span class="token operator">=</span> <span class="token punctuation">{</span> symbol<span class="token punctuation">:</span> <span class="token string">"value"</span> <span class="token punctuation">}</span>\nhash<span class="token punctuation">[</span><span class="token symbol">:symbol</span><span class="token punctuation">]</span> <span class="token comment" spellcheck="true"># => "value"</span>\n</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<h4>More Information:</h4>\n<p><a href=\'https://ruby-doc.org/core-2.4.2/Hash.html\' target=\'_blank\' rel=\'nofollow\'>Ruby hash documentation</a></p>',fields:{slug:"/ruby/ruby-hashes/"},frontmatter:{title:"Ruby Hashes"}}},pathContext:{slug:"/ruby/ruby-hashes/"}}}});
